04085nam a22006615i 9780271078137DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20212009pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710781377 a10.1515/97802710781372doi  a(DE-B1597)584530  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBR560.L34bH23 2009 7aREL0330002bisacsh04a277.48/15072221 aHäberlein, Mark, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Practice of Pluralism :bCongregational Life and Religious Diversity in Lancaster, Pennsylvania, 1730-1820 /cMark Häberlein. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMax Kade Research Institute: Germans Beyond Europe00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 A Quest for Order: The German Reformed Congregation, 1733-1775 -- t2 Growth and Disruption: Lutherans and Moravians -- t3 The English Churches of Colonial Lancaster -- t4 Religious Pluralism in an Eighteenth-Century Town -- t5 Lancaster's Churches in the New Republic -- t6 The Transformation of Charity, 1750-1820 -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe clash of modernity and an Amish buggy might be the first image that comes to one's mind when imagining Lancaster, Pennsylvania, today. But in the early to mid-eighteenth century, Lancaster stood apart as an active and religiously diverse, ethnically complex, and bustling city. On the eve of the American Revolution, Lancaster's population had risen to nearly three thousand inhabitants; it stood as a center of commerce, industry, and trade. While the German-speaking population-Anabaptists as well as German Lutherans, Moravians, and German Calvinists-made up the majority, about one-third were English-speaking Anglicans, Catholics, Presbyterians, Quakers, Calvinists, and other Christian groups. A small group of Jewish families also lived in Lancaster, though they had no synagogue. Carefully mining historical records and documents, from tax records to church membership rolls, Mark Häberlein confirms that religion in Lancaster was neither on the decline nor rapidly changing; rather, steady and deliberate growth marked a diverse religious population.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aReligious pluralismzPennsylvaniazLancasterxHistoryy18th century. 0aReligious pluralismzPennsylvaniazLancasterxHistoryy19th century. 7aRELIGION / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271078137zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271078137423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271078137.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK